## PART 5 — Microservice Readiness & Domain Splitting

Your backend is currently a modular monolith. Converting directly to microservices today would introduce premature distributed network latency. However, you should architect strict logical boundaries now so they can be extracted cleanly into independent containers at Series A scale.

### Recommended Microservice Boundaries

```mermaid
graph TD
    Client[Web UI / CLI / Webhooks] --> APIGateway[API Gateway / Auth Layer]
    
    subgraph Core [Core Domain Services]
        APIGateway --> CoreService[Core Orchestrator Service<br/>Projects, Workspaces, RBAC]
        APIGateway --> BillingService[Billing & Subscription Service<br/>Stripe, Usage Metering]
    end
    
    subgraph Execution [Async Execution Engine]
        CoreService -->|Enqueues Job| BullMQ[Redis Message Bus]
        BullMQ --> RunnerService[Pipeline Runner Worker<br/>Provider Abstraction, Jenkins/GHA]
        RunnerService --> DeployService[Infrastructure Deployer<br/>AWS ECS, ALB, Terraform]
    end
    
    subgraph Observability [Telemetry & AI]
        RunnerService --> LogService[Audit & Log Streaming Service<br/>WebSockets, CloudWatch]
        CoreService --> AIService[AI Assistant Service<br/>Ollama / LLM Engine]
    end
```

### Split vs. Keep Together Rationale
* **Extract Immediately into Independent Worker:** `Pipeline Runner Worker` and `Infrastructure Deployer`. These perform heavy network I/O, long polling, and cloud SDK operations. If an AWS deployment hangs or crashes, it should never impact the REST API serving user dashboards.
* **Keep Together (Monolith Core):** Projects, Workspaces, Users, and RBAC should remain unified in the core relational database to ensure high-speed transactional integrity and ACID compliance.

