## PART 6 — DevOps & Infrastructure Architecture

### Infrastructure Critique
1. **Docker Isolation:** Your Jenkins script runs `docker build` and `docker push` directly on the host worker daemon. A malicious tenant building a Dockerfile with `--network=host` or privileged volume mounts can compromise the underlying Jenkins EC2 instance. **Fix:** Transition to rootless container builders like **Kaniko**, **BuildKit in Kubernetes**, or ephemeral **AWS CodeBuild** instances.
2. **Polling vs. Event-Driven:** Polling Jenkins via REST APIs consumes immense CPU cycles. **Fix:** Configure Jenkins/GitHub Actions to fire **Webhooks** back to an API endpoint (`POST /webhooks/jenkins`) when builds complete, shifting from a polling model to a pure event-driven webhook architecture.
3. **Rate Limiting & Resilience:** There are no rate limiters (e.g., `express-rate-limit` or Redis token bucket) on `/login`, `/signup`, or `/build`. Brute-force attacks or runaway scripts can overwhelm your API and AWS ECR quotas. Add **Circuit Breakers** (using libraries like `opossum`) around AWS SDK and Jenkins REST calls to prevent cascading system failures when external cloud APIs experience outages.

