## PART 7 — Comprehensive Security Review

### Vulnerability Scorecard

| Vulnerability Category | Severity | Findings & Impact | Remediation Strategy |
| :--- | :---: | :--- | :--- |
| **Broken Authentication** | 🔴 CRITICAL | `jwt.decode()` used instead of `jwt.verify()`. Signatures are bypassed. Attackers can forge JWTs and take over admin accounts. | Immediately replace line 15 in `authorize.js` with `jwt.verify(token, process.env.JWT_SECRET)`. |
| **Command Injection** | 🔴 CRITICAL | `generateTenantScript` interpolates user strings into bash scripts. Backticks or subshells in branch names can execute arbitrary shell commands. | Never pass untrusted strings to bash scripts. Use parameterized SDK APIs or pass variables via encrypted environment files. |
| **Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR)** | 🟠 HIGH | `fetchProjects` verifies user ID exists, but does not bind the project query to that user (`WHERE id = $1 AND user_id = $2`). | Always append tenant ownership predicates (`AND org_id = $tenantId`) to every SQL query. |
| **Host Docker Exploitation** | 🟠 HIGH | Tenants execute `docker build` on shared Jenkins EC2 hosts without container isolation. | Run builds inside isolated ephemeral micro-VMs (AWS Fargate tasks or Firecracker micro-VMs). |
| **Hardcoded Credentials** | 🟡 MEDIUM | Sample secrets and ECR registry IDs hardcoded or present in commented `.env` blocks. | Migrate all secrets to AWS Secrets Manager or HashiCorp Vault. Use IAM Roles for Service Accounts (IRSA). |

